</sentence>

</para>
     
 
<para xml:id="C9.S1.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C9.S1.p3.s1">
The main functions treated in this chapter are the Airy functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p3.m1">\mathrm{Ai}\left(z\right)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p3.m2">\mathrm{Bi}\left(z\right)</Math> , and the Scorer functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p3.m3">\mathrm{Gi}(z)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p3.m4">\mathrm{Hi}(z)</Math> (also known as inhomogeneous Airy functions).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C9.S1.p4">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.s1">
Other notations that have been used are as follows: <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m1">\mathrm{Ai}\left(-x\right)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m2">\mathrm{Bi}\left(-x\right)</Math> for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m3">\mathrm{Ai}\left(x\right)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m4">\mathrm{Bi}\left(x\right)</Math> (Jeffreys (1928), later changed to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m5">\mathrm{Ai}\left(x\right)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m6">\mathrm{Bi}\left(x\right)</Math> ); <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m9">U(x)=\sqrt{\pi}\mathrm{Bi}\left(x\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m10">V(x)=\sqrt{\pi}\mathrm{Ai}\left(x\right)</Math> (Fock (1945)); <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m12">A(x)=3^{-\ifrac{1}{3}}\pi\mathrm{Ai}\left(-3^{-\ifrac{1}{3}}x\right)</Math> (Szegő (1967, §1.81));
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.s2">
<Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m15">e_{0}(x)=\pi\mathrm{Hi}(-x)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C9.S1.p4.m16">\widetilde{e}_{0}(x)=-\pi\mathrm{Gi}(-x)</Math> (Tumarkin (1959)).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</section>
